Below is a simple C program that performs a series of floating-point operations. On systems with an FPU, these operations are offloaded to the FPU, improving performance compared to software emulation.

c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <math.h>

int main() {
    double a = 3.14159;
    double b = 2.71828;
    double result;

    // These operations benefit from FPU acceleration
    result = a * b + sqrt(a);
    printf("Result: %f\n", result);

    result = pow(a, 2) + sin(b);
    printf("Result: %f\n", result);

    return 0;
}

Compilers automatically leverage the FPU when available, so no explicit calls are needed. The hardware handles the operations in parallel, reducing CPU load.
